Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new board members for the U.S. central bank, the Federal Reserve, gives Americans – and the U.S. Congress – the opportunity to reflect on the world's most important central bank and its future path.
The obvious first question to ask is how it was possible for the Fed to so utterly fail to meet its most important mandate – price stability.
The fact that the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation indicates a fundamental failure.
Now, institutional exploration of conscience is certainly called for.
But while monetary policy makes headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
The English translation of the given German sentence is:  "Therefore, another major question is whether it will use its enormous power to advance climate or social policy."
The Fed could, for example, refuse loans to companies in the fossil fuel sector, it could require banks to only extend credits to companies with certified net-zero emissions plans, or steer credit allocation towards desired alternatives.
Additionally, it could decide to explicitly incorporate regulation for equality or ethnic justice, by dictating to banks where and to whom loans should be granted, who should be hired and who fired, and so on.
But before we address the question of which direction regulation of the Fed will or should take, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's grave failure.
In 2008, the US government made a consequential decision: while financial institutions could continue to primarily obtain funds for risky investments by selling short-term, volatile debt instruments, a plethora of new regulatory bodies would henceforth assess the risk exposure of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that regulatory agencies would no longer overlook significant chunks of risky assets on bank balance sheets to the extent they did with subprime mortgages.
However, over the following ten years of more detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the regulatory army of the Fed did not once question what actually happens in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic did indeed arrive at the beginning of 2020, the Fed abandoned its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened on an even larger scale.
In March, the investment banks proved unable to act as intermediaries in the market for ordinary US Treasury bonds.
Therefore, Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the issues with the Federal Reserve's liquidity rules. The corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been pushed to the side.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed again saved the money market funds.
Nothing is easier to remedy than runs on the money market, but such things never occurred.
Furthermore, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially providing a guarantee on the principle of "whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Federal Reserve and the US Department of the Treasury had resisted the idea of raising the market price for all mortgages as part of the financial industry rescue package - the Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP).
However, in the year 2020, an explicit lower bound for corporate bond prices was introduced, among other things, with the "Powell put."
The predictable rebuttal to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks because the Fed and the U.S. Treasury Department will simply extinguish any new fire with a new flood of money.
The problem lies, of course, in the incentives that these strategies have created.
Why bother with the trouble of using emergency funds or balance sheet buffers for purchases when prices are falling, providing liquidity, or treating a "fire sale" as an "opportunity to buy"?
The Fed will overwhelm all of them and harvest the profits.
Why issue stocks as a company when one can simply take out a loan, knowing that the state will support the debts or help the company out of trouble, as was the case with airlines?
Why hesitate as an investor when it comes to buying dubious papers, when their value is guaranteed through another "whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed during bad times?
It's no wonder that America is sinking into debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will bear the losses during the next market downturn.
Student loans, government pensions, and mortgages are piling up and waiting for their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue operation.
However, each new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to put more money into rescue actions, and people will not be happy with trillions of newly printed money.
If the rescue packages expected by all fail to materialize, we will wake up in a major crisis—and the fire department will be burnt down.
In 2008, regulatory bodies and lawmakers at least still recognized the moral risk and were concerned that during good times investors would reap profits while during bad times taxpayers would have to bear the losses.
In 2020, there was debate about whether rescue operations were becoming nothing more than self-congratulation.
The exact same central bank that in 2008 failed to see the risks of subprime mortgages just as much as it failed to anticipate the pandemic in 2020 is also eager to conduct stress tests in light of “climate risks.” It is certain to overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy, or some other disruptive event.
The regulators at the Fed do not even ask about the mentioned events.
And even though alphabets of phrases on “networks,” “strategic interactions,” “network effects,” and “credit cycles” are produced, it has not been possible to define the “systemic” risk in any substantive way, beyond it becoming a catch-all term that empowers regulatory agencies with sweeping authority.
Regulatory bodies will never be able to predict all risks, accurately measure the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that enormous debts can always be paid.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system where the state always ends up with mountains of debt during bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
Better regulation can bridge partisan political divides.
The Left is correct when it argues that the large banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit most Americans very little.
However, she is assuming the wrong cause.
The immense effort required to comply with regulations represents a significant obstacle to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is pointless.
Regulatory provisions are either smart or dumb, effective or ineffective, riddled with unwanted consequences or well-designed.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and requires regulators to have no clairvoyant abilities.
The Fed has scandalously stopped companies in the Narrow Banking and payment services sectors, which could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before she devotes herself to the rescue of the planet and the restitution for injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how inadequately it fulfills its fundamental task of protecting the financial system.
